questions.name: Targeted Outcomes
questions.tooltip: The Impact Genome outcomes are an evidence-based set of common goals or objectives that social impact organizations endeavor to achieve. If you feel that one or more of your program's outcomes is missing, please note that below.
questions.questionbody: Identify the outcome(s) your program aims to produce. (select all that apply)

outcome.name: Enhance Arts Appreciation
outcome.description: The demonstration of engaging in art projects that develop an appreciation of arts.
outcome.definition: This outcome is satisfied if an individual has demonstrated at least one of the following within the past year: - Engagement with art projects that develop cultural, educational, heritage, and scientific values - Increased appreciation of arts
outcome.display: Enhance Arts Appreciation - The demonstration of engaging in art projects that develop an appreciation of arts.

outcome.name: Reach Diverse Audiences
outcome.description: The attainment of awareness and interest in the arts community, including the establishment of more points of entry for audiences (e.g., free shows, creative use of public spaces, etc.).
outcome.definition: This outcome is satisfied if an individual of a targeted audience has achieved all of the following within the past year: - Engaged in art projects in their community - Has a diverse range of points of entry to art (e.g., free shows, special invitations to events, creative use of public spaces, etc.)
outcome.display: Reach Diverse Audiences - The attainment of awareness and interest in the arts community, including the establishment of more points of entry for audiences (e.g., free shows, creative use of public spaces, etc.).

outcome.name: Advocacy and Issue Awareness (Individuals)
outcome.description: The demonstration of increased awareness of social issues leading to self-awareness and a change in social norms
outcome.definition:
This outcome is satisfied if an individual has demonstrated at least one of the following within the past year: 

- Self-awareness of their role and impact regarding a certain issue
- A change in social norms to align with a policy position (e.g., beliefs, attitudes, values, etc.)
outcome.display: Advocacy and Issue Awareness (Individuals) - The demonstration of increased awareness of social issues leading to self-awareness and a change in social norms

outcome.name: Advocacy and Issue Awareness (Organizations)
outcome.description: The demonstration of increased awareness of social issues leading to a change in social norms to align with a policy position.
outcome.definition:
This outcome is satisfied if an organization has demonstrated at least one of the following within the past year: 

- Establishment of a system to reach targeted audiences, using a large number and variety of mediums (e.g., social media, word of mouth, newsletters, etc.)
- Self-awareness among a majority of participants of their role and impact regarding a certain issue
- A change in social norms to align with a policy position (e.g., beliefs, attitudes, values, etc.)
outcome.display: Advocacy and Issue Awareness (Organizations) - The demonstration of increased awareness of social issues leading to a change in social norms to align with a policy position.

outcome.name: Use of Data and Evaluation
outcome.description: The demonstration of effective use of data and evaluation, including use of tools and continuous improvement plans.
outcome.definition:
This outcome is satisfied if an organization has demonstrated at least one of the following within the past year:

- Improvement and effective use of data collection and analysis resources and methods (e.g. database management, survey design and distribution, use of analytic software, staff/human capacity)
- Creation or improvement of evaluation tools (e.g. logic model, theory of change, measurement plans)
- Use of continuous quality improvement cycles, leveraging feedback of results into the program?s evaluation strategy
outcome.display: Use of Data and Evaluation - The demonstration of effective use of data and evaluation, including use of tools and continuous improvement plans.

At-risk of Literal Homelessness (15 - 60 days) - Current housing (or available alternative housing) is safe - Must leave current housing or institution (e.g., hospital, jail) within 15-60 days - Does not have other housing options, financial resources, and/or support networks to maintain or obtain a safe place to stay after the next 15-60 days

questions.name: Supporting Evidence location
questions.tooltip: Please write in third-person as this response will appear on your Impact Genome® Scorecard.
questions.questionbody: Describe how you calculated or estimated the number of achieved outcomes, including: - the data point(s) that your calculation/estimation is based on - how you interpreted those data points - source of those data points

questions.name: Types of Evidence
questions.tooltip: If you are unsure, please provide your best guess or reach out to help@impactgenome.org to discuss. Also, our team will review your response and will reach out if we have any recommendations.
questions.questionbody: Select the type of data you collected to determine the number of achieved outcomes.

responsevalue.text: Output metrics - Data that directly quantifies beneficiary participation through measures like attendance rates, students served, workshops held

inputdata.text: Anecdotal evidence or indirect measurement - Testimonials or case studies from participants, or estimates of effectiveness provided by program facilitators
Point-in-time study - Evidence of success that comes from a study or survey of the program's impact on beneficiaries at a single point in time (i.e. at the end of the program)

Pre-post, cross-sectional, or difference-in-difference study (non-randomized control) -Evidence of success that comes from a study or survey of the program's impact on beneficiaries over a period of time and/or across populations without a randomized control group
Randomized control study - Evidence of success that comes from a study or survey of the program's impact on beneficiaries compared to a randomized control group
